{"type":"message","id":"1d8afd69","parentId":"6348f196","timestamp":"2026-03-22T23:19:08.071Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the graph shows that `BlockManager` has no incoming edges (nothing depends on it) and only has outgoing decorator edges (3 `property` decorators). The static analyzer isn't picking up composition/association relationships — only explicit references like function calls, imports, and inheritance.\n\nThe issue is that `query_causes` returns 0 because nothing in the codebase explicitly calls or references `BlockManager`'s constructor or methods in a way the static analyzer detects. This is expected for a class used via composition — the static analyzer sees the `import` and `class` definitions but not the instantiation relationships.\n\nThis is actually a known limitation from the memory: \"No git remote configured yet\", \"Intra-module edges not tracked at method granularity (only module level)\". The static analyzer captures import-level edges but misses runtime instantiation.\n\n\nThe real question is whether the \"No results found\" message is actually misleading — the query is working and finding 3 results, but they're just external decorators scoring below the threshold, so nothing displays. The queries that found nothing earlier likely failed at the entity resolution step rather than the scoring step. These are all external nodes with no useful information, so they're getting filtered out by the scoring system.\n\nThe real problem is the user experience: when resolution fails, I should let them know rather than silently returning nothing. I could improve entity extraction and resolution to be more robust, and when I do return results, I should filter out unhelpful external decorator hits.\n\nLet me verify the \"no results\" issue I saw earlier — it might have been because the resolution failed silently or the results were all filtered.","thinkingSignature":"46ae2b3e923a28e62db1fa1820fda4e5af97